        <abstract>
            <p>Sends CD his photo</p> 
<p>and a copy of his address at Hartford ["Change by gradual modification not the universal law", <hi rend="italic">Proc. Am. Assoc. Adv. Sci.</hi> (1874) pt 2: 7–12]. Does not believe his observations are unfavourable to natural selection but feels there are other factors involved in the origin of form.</p> 
            <p>Discusses further his work on colour and sex in plants; the linking of high colour and maleness.</p>
        </abstract>
